explanation:
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: The macro expands the table lookup used to obtain 'impl'. It may expand to calls or string/byte comparisons (or to OS_ObjectIndexFromToken); you must inspect its expansion to see if memcmp on null-terminated strings is used.
OS_impl_condvar_table: The concrete table/object being indexed by the macro. Its type/contents or helper code associated with it might perform comparisons (e.g. name lookups) that could use memcmp.
OS_object_token_t: The token type is dereferenced and passed to the table-get macro; its definition is needed to trace how the token value is consumed and whether a string comparison occurs.
OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Listed as a callee in the static graph and commonly used by table-get helpers; you must inspect its implementation (or any variant called by the macro) to determine if it uses memcmp to compare null-terminated strings.
OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t: The struct type of 'impl' is needed to confirm the nature of members accessed (impl->mut) — to ensure no string operations occur when accessing fields.
pthread_mutex_unlock: The standard POSIX call used here; include its prototype only to confirm that this call is unrelated to string comparisons (to rule it out).
OS_ERROR and OS_SUCCESS: The return macros/enum values used by the function; include their definitions to ensure no hidden side effects or wrappers that perform string comparisons.
